The '''Kiukainen culture''' was the last [[Stone Age]] culture of the southwestern coast of [[Finland]], dating to 2000–1500/1300 BC.<ref name="Cerezo-RománWilliams2017">{{cite book|last1=Cerezo-Román|first1=Jessica|last2=Williams|first2=Howard|last3=Wessman|first3=Anna|title=Cremation and the Archaeology of Death|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M92PDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA206|accessdate=17 October 2017|date=2017-04-27|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780198798118|pages=206–}}</ref> Its material culture combined elements from [[Pit–Comb Ware culture|Pit–Comb Ware]] and [[Corded Ware]] cultures.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kiukaisten kulttuuri|url=http://www.kansallismuseo.fi/fi/kansallismuseo/opetus/opetuspaketit/esihistoria/tietoa/kivikausi/9|accessdate=17 October 2017|publisher=National Museum of Finland}}</ref> The area of Kiukainen culture ranged from the shore of [[Kvarken]] to [[Vyborg Bay]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Kiukaisten keramiikka|url=http://www.helsinki.fi/hum/arla/keram/kiukais.html|accessdate=17 October 2017|date=25 March 1999|publisher=University of Helsinki}}</ref>

